  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Establish global standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering cases\n- Sharing of financial intelligence\n- Extradition agreements\n- Cross-border law enforcement cooperation\n\n3. Regulatory Frameworks\n- Countries implement consistent anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) protocols\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Financial institutions required to follow international AML standards\n- Due diligence procedures\n- Transaction monitoring\n- Risk assessment protocols\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International economic sanctions\n- Asset freezing\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Information Sharing Platforms\n- Interpol financial crime databases\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n- Global information exchange networks\n\nThese intersection points help create a comprehensive, coordinated approach to preventing and detecting money laundering internationally.",
